b'' b'' b'' b' motif managers take a very simplistic approach to the way they handle events' b' for gadgets: they track for all events(such as motion notify) wether or not' b' the gadget expresses interest in the events. as a result, gadgets typically' b' generate a great deal more network traffic. those with x terminals might find' b' a noticable network performance drop as a result.' b' b" really? what's the point using gadgets then?" b'' b' it is a case of memory vs. network performance tradeoff. gadgets' b' save both client and server memory. but memory is easily expandable while' b' network performance is not, so if i were designing motif i would' b' at least make it *possible* to avoid using gadgets. at present you' b" really don't have a choice because motif forces you to use gadgets" b' in menus and in various other places.' b'' b' adrian nye' b" o'reilly and associates, inc." b'' b'' b"i've been using the xmgraph widget that's been floating around and i" b'noticed the performance is significantly better using gadgets, perhaps' b'even faster. i had heard in an old programming course that gadgets' b"were no longer any benefit to performance, and that it's just as well" b'to use widgets everywhere. so why would pushbutton gadgets be a lot' b'quicker than pushbuttons in the graph? should i start putting gadgets' b'back into my long pulldown menus?' b'' b'xmgraph manages children connected by xmarc widgets in a directed network' b'type graph with automatic layout capability.' b'' b'' b'bill' b'' b'---------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'schlumberger geco-prakla' 